00:17:03,400 --> 00:17:09,120
they died because their product got too slow. And 
so some companies have initial product market fit  

186
00:17:09,120 --> 00:17:16,080
and then they don't keep up. So I do think a lot 
of it is it's very hard to grow that fast. And so  

187
00:17:16,080 --> 00:17:23,200
things really do start breaking, but then once you 
get all the right leadership in place, processes  

188
00:17:23,200 --> 00:17:28,360
in place, then it starts to get better. So it 
goes through ups and downs in level of chaos.

189
00:17:28,360 --> 00:17:30,120
There's one takeaway here that product market fit  

190
00:17:30,120 --> 00:17:33,840
solves a lot of problems. 
Strong product market fit.

191
00:17:33,840 --> 00:17:37,840
Well, no product market fit is 
a death sentence. I would say  

192
00:17:37,840 --> 00:17:44,040
it more like that. If you built a product 
that people aren't really excited to use,  

193
00:17:44,040 --> 00:17:49,560
then you don't have a company because it's very 
hard to do that unless you have distribution  

194
00:17:49,560 --> 00:17:54,400
machine and then you catch up over time. 
But we will not name companies like that.  

195
00:17:54,400 --> 00:18:00,880
So there are other ways of doing it, but 
yeah, that is the most important thing.

196
00:18:00,880 --> 00:18:04,960
Yeah. I will say during my experience 
at Airbnb, I absolutely saw this. It was  

197
00:18:04,960 --> 00:18:11,120
just nonstop chaos. And I always felt like, 
well, how is this continuing to operate and  

198
00:18:11,120 --> 00:18:15,760
succeed? Things are just out of control. 
Everything's changing every six months.  

199
00:18:15,760 --> 00:18:20,080
I don't know what's happening here. And I 
think a lesson here is just that's normal  

200
00:18:20,080 --> 00:18:24,640
for a hyper growth business that has 
strong product market fit. But again,  

201
00:18:24,640 --> 00:18:30,000
not a good excuse to just allow chaos. And 
it's not like chaos means success, right?

202
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:34,800
And it's not a good excuse to not have an 
organization that's functioning. You should still  

203
00:18:34,800 --> 00:18:39,800
strive to have an organization that's functioning 
and keep people happy and motivated and all that.

204
00:18:39,800 --> 00:18:46,280
Great. Okay. Another maybe contrarian 
opinion that you hold along the career  

205
00:18:46,280 --> 00:18:52,560
track is that you don't need to plan your 
career. I also 100% agree with this. I had  

206
00:18:52,560 --> 00:18:55,920
no plan for my career. I never knew where 
the hell I was going to go. I never had  

207
00:18:55,920 --> 00:18:59,720
this vision of here's what I want to do. 
I just followed things that were pulling  

208
00:18:59,720 --> 00:19:04,040
me and things that seemed interesting. I love 
that you also tell people this. I'd love to  

209
00:19:04,040 --> 00:19:07,240
hear your insights here. Especially for someone 
that's either struggling with their career or  

210
00:19:07,240 --> 00:19:12,280
just stressed. They don't have a plan or their 
plan's not working the way they wanted it to.

211
00:19:12,280 --> 00:19:16,560
Really recently I was talking to somebody in 
their twenties who was asking me for career  

212
00:19:16,560 --> 00:19:23,280
advice. Should I be a product manager, et cetera. 
And I'm trying to put together my five-year plan  

213
00:19:23,280 --> 00:19:29,040
and I said, "I never had a five-year plan." 
So to be clear, some people need that.  

214
00:19:29,040 --> 00:19:34,360
That's the kind of people they are. They want the 
planning. I said, "It's great if you want that,  

215
00:19:34,360 --> 00:19:42,320
but I never had it." And the person I was talking 
to just relaxed and they're like, "Oh my God,  

216
00:19:42,320 --> 00:19:46,760
that's so great to hear because I have no idea 
what I want to do in five years." I'm like,  

217
00:19:46,760 --> 00:19:51,160
"I still have no idea what I want to do in five 
years. I've never had an idea what I want to do in  

218
00:19:51,160 --> 00:19:59,240
five years." Early in your career you have a lot 
more angst about it because the forks in the road  

219
00:19:59,240 --> 00:20:04,560
are more significant because they can go, do 
I go get an MBA or do I go work for somebody?  

220
00:20:04,560 --> 00:20:09,000
Do I be a product manager or an engineer? And 
those really take you in very different paths. 

221
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:14,160
And I meet a lot of kids in their ... I 
shouldn't call them kids. My kids are my  

222
00:20:14,160 --> 00:20:21,040
kids' friends. But a lot of people who are 
younger in their career who are struggling  

223
00:20:21,040 --> 00:20:26,480
with this a little bit. So what I believe, 
and I've always believed is that you follow  

224
00:20:26,480 --> 00:20:33,880
people. You learn the most from people. I don't 
look for domains. Some people have a domain,  

225
00:20:33,880 --> 00:20:40,000
like I'm super interested in climate or whatever 
and they really want to work in that area and  

226
00:20:40,000 --> 00:20:46,960
that's fine so maybe within that area. But you 
follow people who are the best at what they do.  

227
00:20:46,960 --> 00:20:52,520
So it's not good enough to follow somebody who 
you like. You want to follow somebody who's either  

228
00:20:52,520 --> 00:20:57,720
the best product thinker or the best engineer 
or the best salesperson. And so that you will  

229
00:20:57,720 --> 00:21:03,680
learn the skill of how to be the best at that.
So you follow people where you're going to learn  

230
00:21:03,680 --> 00:21:08,760
the most. And a way to do that also is you look 
at where the great people are going. So you want  

231
00:21:08,760 --> 00:21:16,120
to go to companies where there's also a nexus 
of great people because they together will do  

232
00:21:16,120 --> 00:21:22,120
great things. And even if the company fails 
or succeeds, but not as much as you'd like,  

233
00:21:22,120 --> 00:21:28,720
you still have those connections. Everybody talks 
about the PayPal Mafia and how they've gone on  

234
00:21:28,720 --> 00:21:35,800
to do things. I was super lucky to be at Google 
for so many years and I spent a lot of time with  

235
00:21:35,800 --> 00:21:40,120
Googlers that I met and that are all working 
in different companies now because you build  

236
00:21:40,120 --> 00:21:45,000
those relationships by working together. So 
if you follow people and where you're going  

237
00:21:45,000 --> 00:21:53,400
to learn the most and you go step by step, I think 
that's a great way of progressing in your career.

238
00:21:53,400 --> 00:21:59,240
That's such tactical advice. And I've seen this 
work for a lot of people that just go where their  

239
00:21:59,240 --> 00:22:04,600
favorite former employees work. And not favorite 
to your point, but the people that they most  

240
00:22:04,600 --> 00:22:11,880
respect and have been most impressed by. And 
I think it's such an easy thing to do. It's a  

241
00:22:11,880 --> 00:22:16,800
really easy heuristic for understanding where to 
go. There's something Marc Andreessen once shared  

242
00:22:16,800 --> 00:22:22,280
that I'm reminded of when you say this. There's 
a term for this, I forget the actual term, but  

243
00:22:22,280 --> 00:22:27,880
there's certain companies have this gravitational 
pull where they are acquiring all the best talent.  

244
00:22:27,880 --> 00:22:33,760
They're currently the gravity in the space and 
everyone awesome is going there. And you have to,  

245
00:22:33,760 --> 00:22:36,480
as a company, know you're one of those 
companies or you're the opposite. You're  

246
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:41,600
losing all the people and they're all going to 
this other company. I guess any thoughts on that?

247
00:22:43,280 --> 00:22:49,280
Yeah. And it's really bad when you don't have 
a gravitational pull. It's super hard. I would  

248
00:22:49,280 --> 00:22:53,600
say that one thing that if you're a 
manager, I always advise managers,  

249
00:22:53,600 --> 00:23:01,200
go somewhere where you can recruit. I got a piece 
of advice from a friend that I thought was amazing  

250
00:23:01,200 --> 00:23:10,120
advice as a leader. She said to me, "Take a 
job where if you hire people, it's going to  

251
00:23:10,120 --> 00:23:19,040
make their careers." I was like, "Whoa." Because 
I was getting offers for some turnaround jobs.  

252
00:23:19,040 --> 00:23:25,360
And if you think you can turn around, great. 
But if you're going to hire the best people,  

253
00:23:25,360 --> 00:23:28,920
you want to make sure that it's going to be a good 
place for them and that they're going to learn and  

254
00:23:28,920 --> 00:23:33,840
they're going to grow. And so you want to do 
right by them. And you really earnestly want  

255
00:23:33,840 --> 00:23:41,200
to say you can make your career by coming here.
And I thought that gave such a higher bar for  

256
00:23:41,200 --> 00:23:47,760
every job I was looking at as a leader that I 
thought it was just amazing advice. And then  

257
00:23:47,760 --> 00:23:55,040
on the flip side, on the negative side, some 
people are putting too much emphasis on where  

258
00:23:55,040 --> 00:24:01,440
will I get a big financial return? And I've 
found that financial returns are the hardest  

259
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:06,800
to predict. You know who's good. You know who 
you want to work with. You can predict where  

260
00:24:06,800 --> 00:24:12,520
you're going to learn. Because even if a company 
fails, you learn a lot. But predicting financial  

261
00:24:12,520 --> 00:24:20,080
success is so hard because you don't know what's 
going to happen with the market, with the world,  

262
00:24:20,080 --> 00:24:26,280
with crypto, and Meta AI. And people who 
do that and say ... I had one person say,  

263
00:24:26,280 --> 00:24:32,400
"I took this job because I'm a mercenary. They 
just paid me a ton." Did not work out for him.  

264
00:24:32,400 --> 00:24:40,440
And I feel really bad when people do that, 
but I think that it's a dangerous thing to do.

265
00:24:40,440 --> 00:24:43,920
I imagine some people hearing this 
advice are going to feel like,  

266
00:24:43,920 --> 00:24:49,160
"I'm not going to get a job at 
OpenAI or Glean or other awesome  

267
00:24:49,160 --> 00:24:52,880
companies that everyone wants to go 
work at." Any advice to those folks?

268
00:24:52,880 --> 00:24:56,480
There's lots of good companies and 
there's lots of smart people. You  

269
00:24:56,480 --> 00:25:00,480
don't have to be at the top brand. And 
if you go somewhere where you're going  

270
00:25:00,480 --> 00:25:06,040
to learn and it's going to get you there. 
I made mistakes. I went to some companies,  

271
00:25:06,040 --> 00:25:11,680
multiple companies that failed or stopped growing 
and didn't do well or didn't have all the right  

272
00:25:11,680 --> 00:25:18,120
people. Careers you don't make every step is to 
the right place. You remember in what you cited,  

273
00:25:18,120 --> 00:25:21,960
all the companies I went to that did well, you 
left out all the ones that I went to that didn't  

274
00:25:21,960 --> 00:25:26,160
do well. And so then people will assume that 
every time I made a job change, it was to a  

275
00:25:26,160 --> 00:25:33,480
company that did well. No. That was not the 
case. So if you focus on that learning bit,  

276
00:25:33,480 --> 00:25:42,120
you will get there. And there are lots of paths. 
There isn't just the OpenAI or Glean or Anthropic.

277
00:25:42,120 --> 00:25:46,440
Awesome. And again, I love how tactical this 
is. If someone is trying to figure out where  

278
00:25:46,440 --> 00:25:50,280
to go work if they're unhappy in their current 
job or don't have a job right now is just make  

279
00:25:50,280 --> 00:25:53,880
a list of the people you most respect 
that are the best at the thing they do,  

280
00:25:53,880 --> 00:25:57,960
see where they work and there's your list of 
companies to potentially go after. There's a  

281
00:25:57,960 --> 00:26:01,640
lot of benefits to this as you shared. It's 
not just helping you pick the place to work,  

282
00:26:01,640 --> 00:26:05,840
it's the network. It'll level you up. Is 
there anything else along those lines that  

283
00:26:05,840 --> 00:26:10,400
is helpful for people to think about 
why this is a really good strategy?

284
00:26:10,400 --> 00:26:12,920
Skills can't be taken away. A company can fail,  

285
00:26:12,920 --> 00:26:16,840
but if you learn a skill, you 
will always have that skill.

286
00:26:16,840 --> 00:26:20,600
I love that. And I've totally seen this to 
work, so I really love that you're focusing  

287
00:26:20,600 --> 00:26:26,040
on this advice. You've mentioned places you've 
worked and folks you've worked with. You worked  

288
00:26:26,040 --> 00:26:31,760
with folks like Jeff Bezos, Stewart Butterfield, 
some of the top product thinkers, leaders in the  

289
00:26:31,760 --> 00:26:37,000
world. So let me just ask, what's one thing you 
learned from Jeff Bezos and Stewart Butterfield?

290
00:26:37,000 --> 00:26:42,320
Probably can't narrow it down to one, but I'll 
talk about Bezos first. I was very lucky to join  

291
00:26:42,320 --> 00:26:48,600
Amazon early when I still ... I had quarterly 
meetings with Jeff Bezos. And this was before  

292
00:26:48,600 --> 00:26:55,800
AWS launched, so it was before Amazon was known in 
the Valley. This is another example. I went there  

293
00:26:55,800 --> 00:27:00,840
because I went to work for Udi Manbe who started 
A9 and he was talking to me one night trying to  

294
00:27:00,840 --> 00:27:06,040
recruit me and he spent two hours on the phone 
with me telling me how amazing Jeff Bezos was. And  

295
00:27:06,040 --> 00:27:14,320
this was before there were any books on him. And 
that really convinced me to go there. So there's  

296
00:27:14,320 --> 00:27:19,680
a lot written on Bezos. Read his shareholder 
letters, read the books about him, read Colin  

297
00:27:19,680 --> 00:27:24,960
Bryar's Working Backwards. The Everything Box 
I think it's called or The Everything Store.

298
00:27:24,960 --> 00:27:26,120
The Everything Store. Yeah.

299
00:27:27,240 --> 00:27:31,840
There's so many good books and there's so much 
to learn about how he works. So I won't try and  

300
00:27:31,840 --> 00:27:37,400
cover those things. The things that stood out 
to me from the meetings I had with him were  

301
00:27:37,400 --> 00:27:42,800
a couple of things. One, a lot of people have 
written about these six pagers, so he doesn't  

302
00:27:42,800 --> 00:27:48,573
believe in PowerPoint. You write a six pager 
about ... It's like studying for the final exam  

303
00:27:48,573 --> 00:27:53,440
is writing these six pagers. So you go into the 
meeting and there's the people around the table,  

304
00:27:53,440 --> 00:27:58,440
his executive team and him. First he does 
not speak until everybody around the table  

305
00:27:58,440 --> 00:28:03,880
speaks. So he goes around to all his leads and 
said, "What do you think? What do you think?  

306
00:28:03,880 --> 00:28:07,080
What do you think?" And I'm sitting there like, 
"I don't care what anyone think. I just want to  

307
00:28:07,080 --> 00:28:14,680
hear what Bezos thinks." But he wants to make sure 
that it's a team effort and that he's listening to  

308
00:28:14,680 --> 00:28:22,400
what everybody in his organization thinks.
And he always spoke last. He is by far the  

309
00:28:22,400 --> 00:28:30,000
smartest person I've ever met in my life. I've 
worked with a lot of smart people. But his ability  

310
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:39,280
to go deep in any domain and nail the core issue, 
and remember. We would've quarterly meetings and  

311
00:28:39,280 --> 00:28:44,200
from quarter to quarter he would remember things 
that he had talked about before and then he would  

312
00:28:44,200 --> 00:28:50,800
go into the architecture of search and why are 
you doing it this way or that way? And you're just  

313
00:28:50,800 --> 00:28:58,280
blown away that he knows that. For me, the biggest 
takeaway from those meetings was his consistency,  

314
00:28:58,280 --> 00:29:04,600
which is he had principles that it made it easier 
for you to operate in his company because you knew  

315
00:29:04,600 --> 00:29:09,560
what he cared about because he always had these 
principles. Everything had to be customer driven,  

316
00:29:09,560 --> 00:29:16,000
everything had to be relevant for the customer.
He hated icons. That was just the thing. You had  

317
00:29:16,000 --> 00:29:19,640
to write what they were because people couldn't 
figure out what they are. So anytime you showed  

318
00:29:19,640 --> 00:29:25,200
an icon, he would get annoyed. But you would go 
in and after a couple of meetings you're like,  

319
00:29:25,200 --> 00:29:31,040
"Okay. I know what he's going to ask about. I know 
how he's thinking and I know what his principles  

320
00:29:31,040 --> 00:29:38,120
are." And I think that consistency enables you 
to operate a large organization more effectively.  

321
00:29:38,120 --> 00:29:43,760
And then there's one other thing that I really 
remember was one of the few really small meetings  

322
00:29:43,760 --> 00:29:48,560
I was in with him and we were presenting 
working on a new product, and I was like,  

323
00:29:48,560 --> 00:29:54,320
"Our competitors have 10 times as many people as 
we do on this." And he looks at me and he said,  

324
00:29:54,320 --> 00:30:00,360
"That is your advantage." And then he goes into 
his talk about how it's a hill and it takes seven  

325
00:30:00,360 --> 00:30:05,640
years to build a product. You can't look at it in 
the near term. You have to be in it for the long  

326
00:30:05,640 --> 00:30:15,240
term. You can be sure I never went in and said, 
"I need a lot more resources." So that was Bezos.

327
00:30:15,240 --> 00:30:15,960
Awesome.

328
00:30:17,000 --> 00:30:23,240
Stewart. Again, I went to Slack because I wanted 
to work with Stewart Butterfield. I think he  

329
00:30:23,240 --> 00:30:29,280
is the best product thinker in the Valley. 
He's not working in product right now. He's  

330
00:30:29,280 --> 00:30:37,120
taking time off. But he's got this combination of 
long-term thinking and in the details. So in 2014,  

331
00:30:37,120 --> 00:30:43,560
he wrote a master plan for Slack, which was 
build a product people love, build a network.  

332
00:30:43,560 --> 00:30:48,520
That's Slack Connect. Build a platform that makes 
all of your other SaaS products more valuable.  

333
00:30:48,520 --> 00:30:54,640
That's Slack Platform. And then do some magic 
AI stuff. Magic AI stuff took a lot longer, but-

334
00:30:54,640 --> 00:30:56,840
That was part of his plan 
early on is magic AI stuff.

335
00:30:56,840 --> 00:31:03,640
It literally was. There was a grid with four 
boxes in 2014 and it never changed. That was  

336
00:31:03,640 --> 00:31:09,760
his master plan and what we worked on each 
year changed. But somebody recently asked me,  

337
00:31:11,080 --> 00:31:14,920
"You guys did Slack Connect much later?" I'm like, 
"Yeah, but it was always part of the plan." It was  

338
00:31:14,920 --> 00:31:20,720
always part of his vision. So he saw forward in 
the vision, but he also was very much into the  

339
00:31:20,720 --> 00:31:26,480
details. And I think the thing that I learned 
from him the most was the power of prototyping.  

340
00:31:26,480 --> 00:31:31,680
And that even though he was such a great product 
thinker, he would always say, "I can't tell you if  

341
00:31:31,680 --> 00:31:37,000
this is going to work. I have to feel it. I have 
to try it. And a mock-up doesn't tell you what  

342
00:31:37,000 --> 00:31:45,400
it's going to feel like." And he would push people 
to do prototypes, not incremental of just to get a  

343
00:31:45,400 --> 00:31:53,480
feature out, but really to think. Very soon after 
I started, we launched ... I hired a design lead,  

344
00:31:53,480 --> 00:31:59,240
Ethan Eismannn, and he led a redesign of 
the new information architecture for Slack.

345
00:31:59,240 --> 00:32:01,592
I worked with Ethan at Airbnb.

346
00:32:01,592 --> 00:32:01,600
Oh yeah.

347
00:32:01,600 --> 00:32:04,640
He was head of design for the search 
experience and the search team.

348
00:32:04,640 --> 00:32:09,840
Yeah. Ethan is awesome. And he came in and his 
first task was to work with Stewart on this  

349
00:32:09,840 --> 00:32:16,040
redesign. And Stewart came in and said, "I want 
you to take everything in the interface and put  

350
00:32:16,040 --> 00:32:21,600
it behind one button." And everyone's like, 
"That's never going to work." And he's like,  

351
00:32:21,600 --> 00:32:27,360
"Do it. Just do it." And so we had our prototypers 
... We had also engineers, front-end engineers who  

352
00:32:27,360 --> 00:32:31,280
were really good at prototyping, literally 
took everything in the interface and put it  

353
00:32:31,280 --> 00:32:34,600
behind one button and he said, "This is how 
you're going to see what you really need in  

354
00:32:34,600 --> 00:32:43,200
the interface." So we were never going to ship 
that, but it was the beginning of the redesign.

