508
00:45:38,680 --> 00:45:43,480
that I'll quote you here. One of the mistakes that 
I see a lot of product managers make is they over  

509
00:45:43,480 --> 00:45:50,360
index on people who are going to be unhappy with 
the products they're launching. And basically your  

510
00:45:50,360 --> 00:45:56,040
advice is not to worry so much about making users 
unhappy, which I think is counterintuitive to  

511
00:45:56,040 --> 00:45:59,480
some people. Can you just talk about this lesson 
and I'd love to hear what product you launched  

512
00:45:59,480 --> 00:46:04,120
that made people unhappy that you realized, oh, 
maybe we don't need to worry about this as much.

513
00:46:04,120 --> 00:46:12,320
I saw it more when you unlaunch things, you take 
things away there's always some set of users that  

514
00:46:12,320 --> 00:46:19,120
are using a feature that nobody else does, and 
then you take it away and they're super unhappy,  

515
00:46:19,120 --> 00:46:25,200
but there are more people you're going to make 
happy. So a product manager gets caught in this  

516
00:46:25,200 --> 00:46:32,760
trap of the vocal minority and the number 
of people using your product ... Depends on  

517
00:46:32,760 --> 00:46:36,560
what phase. Are you a Google? Are you Slack? Are 
you a Glean? But the number of people using your  

518
00:46:36,560 --> 00:46:42,000
product today is usually unless you're a Google 
far smaller than the number of people who are  

519
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:47,440
going to be using your product tomorrow. So 
design it for the bigger number of people who  

520
00:46:47,440 --> 00:46:52,840
are going to be using it tomorrow. If you have 
to redo the UI and the Who Moved My Cheese,  

521
00:46:52,840 --> 00:46:58,560
people will be unhappy, but all the new people are 
going to be like, "This is so much easier." Then  

522
00:46:58,560 --> 00:47:05,960
do it and deal with the people who are unhappy.
But the trick is you have to be respectful and  

523
00:47:05,960 --> 00:47:11,840
you have to be transparent and you have to 
explain. You have to go to people and say,  

524
00:47:11,840 --> 00:47:16,480
"This is why we made this change." And you have 
to be authentic. You can't be dismissive and  

525
00:47:16,480 --> 00:47:23,720
you can't have marketing speak. You have to really 
say, "Here's for real why." And you have to listen  

526
00:47:23,720 --> 00:47:31,320
to your audience. You don't want to alienate your 
early users because most people ... If you made a  

527
00:47:31,320 --> 00:47:37,680
good decision on why you moved this or why we 
stopped using Slack calls and moved to Huddles  

528
00:47:37,680 --> 00:47:43,680
and you have to do it over time and give people 
choice and then give them enough time to move.  

529
00:47:43,680 --> 00:47:50,040
So you have to do it in the right way. But 
if people feel heard, it makes a difference. 

530
00:47:50,680 --> 00:47:55,520
I have an example that's not a product example, 
but I think is a really good one. It's a  

531
00:47:55,520 --> 00:48:00,600
leadership example. So when I was at Google, 
there was always a controversy about something,  

532
00:48:00,600 --> 00:48:03,960
but there was a controversy about ... It was 
Blogger or something. I can't even remember what  

533
00:48:03,960 --> 00:48:12,720
it was. It was like we made a change. We were like 
50,000 people at the time. There was an engineer  

534
00:48:12,720 --> 00:48:17,440
in my team, an IT engineer that was super unhappy 
about the change. And I knew Rachel Whetstone,  

535
00:48:17,440 --> 00:48:23,760
she was in charge of all of PR and global 
policy at Google. So huge job. And I emailed  

536
00:48:23,760 --> 00:48:28,560
Rachel and I'm like, "Hey, do you have an 
FAQ or something that can help me? Because  

537
00:48:28,560 --> 00:48:33,640
I don't know why you made this change and that 
I can help explain to the engineer in my team." 

538
00:48:33,640 --> 00:48:39,680
She did not respond to my email. She picked up 
the phone and she called him. I had no idea she  

539
00:48:39,680 --> 00:48:45,400
did this. She just called this IT engineer and 
she listened to him and she heard why he was  

540
00:48:45,400 --> 00:48:53,240
upset and she explained her reasoning. He was so 
blown away that she called him that he completely  

541
00:48:53,240 --> 00:48:58,880
changed his opinion and then he told everyone 
else in the org. And so it had this effect.  

542
00:48:58,880 --> 00:49:06,480
And I learned a lot from watching her do that. 
She never even told me she did it later. She  

543
00:49:06,480 --> 00:49:12,600
just did it. You just act. You're authentic. 
You listen to people and you're transparent.

544
00:49:12,600 --> 00:49:16,960
It's so funny. This reminds me of a parenting 
book I'm reading right now that a former guest  

545
00:49:16,960 --> 00:49:24,160
recommended called Listen. And the core thesis 
of the book is when your kids are acting up or  

546
00:49:24,160 --> 00:49:30,560
they're getting off track, so much of what they 
